### Expression Syntax Rules

an expression is a mathematical formula or logical statement used to specify conditional rules or calculate values. With expressions, you can control the flow of your survey, manage question visibility and read-only state, perform in-survey computations, and more. Expressions are evaluated (that is, calculated to produce a result) in real time while a respondent fills out a form. This dynamic evaluation ensures that expression results are always up-to-date.

## Expression Operands

# Question Values

- To use a question value in an expression, specify the Question name property value in curly brackets: {my-question-name}
- {my-question-name[index]}: Use a zero-based index to access value of options in elements can choose one or more options. example: {q1[0]}

# Custom Variables

-  To use a custom variable in an expression, wrap its name in curly brackets, just like you do with question names: {my-custom-variable}

# Function Results

- Calculation functions produce results that can be used as operands in expressions. For example, the dateDiff() function computes a difference between two dates.

## Expression Operators

# Comparison Operators

- empty: Returns true if the value is undefined or null. example: "{q1} empty"
- notempty:	Returns true if the value is different from undefined and null. example: "{q1} notempty"
- <= / lessorequal: Compares two values and returns true if the first is less or equal to the second. example: "{q1} <= 10"
- >= / greaterorequal:	Compares two values and returns true if the first is greater or equal to the second. example: "{q1} >= 10"
- = / == / equal: Compares two values and returns true if they are loosely equal (that is, their type is disregarded). example: "{q1} = 10"
- != / <> / notequal:	Compares two values and returns true if they are not loosely equal. example: "{q1} != 10"
- < / less: Compares two values and returns true if the first is less than the second. example: "{q1} < 10"
- > / greater:	Compares two values and returns true if the first is greater than the second. example: "{q1} > 10"
- *= / contains / contain:	Compares two values and returns true if the first value contains the second value within it. example: "{q1} contains 'abc'"
- notcontains / notcontain:	Compares two values and returns true if the first value doesn't contain the second value within it. example: "{q1} notcontains 'abc'"
- anyof:	Compares a value with an array of values and returns true if the value is present, or compares two arrays and returns true if the first array includes any value from the second. example: "{q1} anyof [ 'value1', 'value2', 'value3' ]"
- noneof:	Compares a value with an array of values and returns true if the value is absent, or compares two arrays and returns true if the first array includes none of the values from the second. example: "{q1} noneof [ 'value1', 'value2', 'value3' ]"
- allof: Compares two arrays and returns true if the first array includes all values from the second. example: "{q1} allof [ 'value1', 'value2', 'value3' ]"

# Logical Operators

- ! / negate:	Returns true if the condition returns false, and vice versa. example	!{q1}
- && / and:	Combines two or more conditions and returns true if all of them are true. example	"{q1} empty and {q2} empty"
- || / or:	Combines two or more conditions and returns true if any of them is true. example	"{q1} empty or {q2} empty"

# Arithmetic Operators

- +: Adds up two values. example	"{q1} + {q2}"
- -: Subtracts the second value from the first. example	"{q1} - {q2}"
- *: Multiplies two values. example	"{q1} * {q2}"
- /: Divides the first value by the second. example	"{q1} / {q2}"
- %: Returns the remainder of the division of the first value by the second. example	"{q1} % {q2}"
- ^ / power: Raises the first value to the power of the second. example	"{q1} ^ {q2}"

## Calculation Functions

# Logical Functions

- Expressions support one logical function—iif. It returns one value or the other based on whether a specified condition is true or false. Example: "iif({q1} > 20, 'High', 'Low')"

# Date Functions

- age: Age according to a given birthdate. example: "age('2000-01-01')"
- currentDate: Current date and time. example:	"currentDate()"
- today:Current date or a date shifted from the current by a given number of days. example: "today(-1)" (yesterday) "today(1)" (tomorrow)
- year: Year of a given date. example: 	"year('2000-01-01')" (2000)
- month: Month of a given date as a value from 1 (January) to 12 (December). example: "month('2000-01-01')" (1)
- day: Day of the month for a given date as a value from 1 to 31. example: 	"day('2000-01-30')" (30)
- weekday: Day of the week for a given date as a value from 0 (Sunday) to 6 (Saturday). example: 	"weekday('2000-01-01')" (6)
- dateDiff: Difference between two given dates in days (default), hours, minutes, seconds, months, or years. example: "dateDiff('2000-01-01', '2000-02-01', "days")" (31)
- dateAdd: A Date value with an added or subtracted number of days (default), hours, minutes, seconds, months, or years. example: "dateAdd('2000-01-01', 10, "days")" (new Date(2000-01-11))

# Aggregation Functions

- sum: Sum of passed numbers. example	"sum(10, 20, 30, 40)" (100)
- min: Minimum of passed numbers. example	"min(10, 20, 30, 40)" (10)
- max: Maximum of passed numbers. example	"max(10, 20, 30, 40)" (40)
- avg: Average of passed numbers. example	"avg(10, 20, 30, 40)" (25)
- sumInArray:	Sum of numbers in a specific matrix column or panel question. 	
- minInArray:	Minimum of numbers in a specific matrix column or panel question. 	
- maxInArray:	Maximum of numbers in a specific matrix column or panel question. 	
- avgInArray:	Average of numbers in a specific matrix column or panel question. 	
- countInArray: Number of matrix rows whose specified column is not empty or number of inner panels whose specified question is not empty. 	

